{"title_page": "Raj Loomba, Baron Loomba", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = The Lord Loomba\n| image = Official portrait of Lord Loomba crop 2, 2019.jpg\n|honorific-suffix  = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]\n|office = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start = 12 January 2011<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1943|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Dhilwan]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      =British\n| spouse           = Veena Chaudhry\n| party            = Non-affiliated\n| alma_mater       = [[State University of Iowa]], United States\n}}\n\n'''Rajinder Paul Loomba, Baron Loomba''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 13 November 1943, [[Dhilwan]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India) is a philanthropist, founder and executive chairman of clothing company Loomba Group, and a member of the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/l/23154/Rajinder%20Paul%20%28Raj%29%20Loomba+LOOMBA.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830132829/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/l/23154/Rajinder%20Paul%20(Raj)%20Loomba+LOOMBA.aspx |archivedate=30 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nLoomba was born as one of seven children in Dhilwan, in the state of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India. He was educated at [[Dayanand Anglo-Vedic Schools System|D.A.V. College]], [[Jallandhar]] and at the [[University of Iowa|State University of Iowa]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asian-whoswho.com/viewasian.asp?aid=9 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051030020021/http://www.asian-whoswho.com/viewasian.asp?aid=9 |archivedate=30 October 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> his family moved to England in 1962. Loomba built up his fashion business from scratch, graduating from a stall at [[Widnes]] market to a shop, a wholesale business and then an import company, Rinku Group Ltd. The company has over 200 retail concession outlets in the UK, offices in London, Delhi and China, and supplies major retail groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theloombafoundation.org/sites/default/files/pdf/LR_9501_Loomba.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323050533/http://www.theloombafoundation.org/sites/default/files/pdf/LR_9501_Loomba.pdf |archivedate=23 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLoomba is a member of the [[Rotary Club]] in [[London]], the [[Institute of Directors]] and is a [[Freeman of the City of London]]. He is Chairman of the Friends of the Three Faiths Forum, is Patron of Children In Need India, and is the Founding Patron of the World Punjabi Organisation.<ref>http://globalpf.org/strategic-advisors.html?show=25</ref> He is Vice President of [[Barnardo\u2019s]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/peers_detail.aspx?name=Lord_Loomba&pPK=d3388ae8-cf3f-435e-9979-92a7aebe7816 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419153712/http://www.libdems.org.uk/peers_detail.aspx?name=Lord_Loomba&pPK=d3388ae8-cf3f-435e-9979-92a7aebe7816 |archivedate=19 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and of the Safer London Foundation, a charity backed by the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/rajinder-loomba/90427 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001202505/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/rajinder-loomba/90427 |archivedate=1 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1997 he was named Asian of the Year UK by Asian Who's Who International.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asian-whoswho.com/viewasian.asp?aid=9 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051030020021/http://www.asian-whoswho.com/viewasian.asp?aid=9 |archivedate=30 October 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLoomba is married to Veena Chaudhry, with whom he has two daughters and one son.\n\n==Charity work==\nLoomba has become well known for his fundraising and campaigning concerning the issue of widowhood in the developing world. His mother, Shrimati Pushpa Wati Loomba, was widowed at the age of 37 in India,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theloombafoundation.org/index.php?q=about/inspiration|title=The Loomba Foundation {{!}} Empowering Widows Worldwide {{!}} Children's Education|website=www.theloombafoundation.org|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref> and Loomba experienced first-hand the social and economic discrimination that widows in that country faced.\n\nIt was in his mother\u2019s memory that Loomba set up his charity, [[The Loomba Foundation]], which works to raise awareness of the issue of widowhood and which raises funds to educate the children of poor widows in India and empower widows in other developing countries in south Asia and across Africa. The flagship of the charity\u2019s awareness campaign is [[International Widows Day]], which takes place annually on 23 June, the anniversary of his mother\u2019s widowhood. Following a sustained campaign, on 21 December 2010 the [[United Nations General Assembly]] formally recognised, by unanimous acclaim, 23 June as International Widows Day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/RES/65/189|title=United Nations Official Document|website=www.un.org|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of his contribution to charity, in the [[2008 Birthday Honours]] Loomba was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE);<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58729 |date=14 June 2008 |page=25 |supp=y}}</ref> he received his award from [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] at a ceremony at [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref>http://www.india-server.com/news/nri-entrepreneur-raj-loomba-receives-cbe-5111.html{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==House of Lords==\nOn 12 January 2011 Loomba was ennobled as a [[life peer]] with the name, style and title of '''Baron Loomba''', of [[Moor Park, Hertfordshire|Moor Park]] in the county of [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59672 |date=17 January 2011 |page=80 }}</ref> He took up his seat in the [[House of Lords]] on 13 January 2011, representing the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12178726 | work=BBC News | title=Downton Abbey creator Julian Fellowes takes Lords seat | date=13 January 2011}}</ref> He was introduced to the House on 17 January 2011, supported by the Lords [[Tom McNally, Baron McNally|McNally]] and [[Navnit Dholakia, Baron Dholakia|Dholakia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2011-01-17b.1.0|title=Introduction: Lord Loomba: 17 Jan 2011: House of Lords debates|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref> On 21 January 2011 he gave his maiden speech in the House during a debate on the Rehabilitation of Offenders (Amendment) Bill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libdemvoice.org/lord-raj-loombas-maiden-speech-22840.html|title=Lord Raj Loomba\u2019s maiden speech|website=Liberal Democrat Voice|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref>\n\nLoomba's company, Rinku Group PLC, had previously made a donation of \u00a32,500 to the leadership campaign of [[Nick Clegg]] in December 2007.<ref>https://pefonline.electoralcommission.org.uk/Search/CommonReturnsSearch.aspx?type=basicDonationSearch Electoral Commission website, register of political donations - EC number C0002451 - donation accepted on 17 December 2002</ref> His nomination to the peerage attracted controversy after it emerged that one of the three members of the [[House of Lords Appointments Commission]] who approved his appointment, Liberal Democrat peer Lord Dholakia, had accepted six overseas trips in the previous four years, paid for by Loomba's charitable foundation, the Loomba Trust. Two of the trips, to [[Toronto]] and [[New York City]], took place during the time the Commission was considering Loomba's appointment.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1333712/Lib-Dem-Lord-Dholakia-row-peerage-friend-Raj-Loomba.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | first=Abul | last=Taher | title=Lib Dem in row over peerage for his friend | date=28 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nLoomba donated more than \u00a3350,000 to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] between 2011 and 2013.\n\nIn December 2016, Lord Loomba left the Liberal Democrats and now sits as a [[Non-affiliated members of the House of Lords|non-affiliated]] Peer.  Explaining his decision he said: \"I now wish to concentrate on issues such as human rights, gender equality, education and above all the United Nations\u2019 2030 Sustainable Development Goals\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiagbnews.com/government/lord-raj-loomba-exits-lib-dem-fold/|title=British Indian Lord Raj Loomba exits Lib Dem fold - IndiaGB News - INDIA UK NEWS {{!}} ANGLO INDIA NEWS {{!}} BRITISH INDIA NEWS {{!}} INDIA EXPORTS NEWS {{!}} UK EXPORTS NEWS {{!}} ASEAN UK NEWS {{!}}INDIA TOURISM{{!}}|date=2016-12-14|work=IndiaGB News - INDIA UK NEWS {{!}} ANGLO INDIA NEWS {{!}} BRITISH INDIA NEWS {{!}} INDIA EXPORTS NEWS {{!}} UK EXPORTS NEWS {{!}} ASEAN UK NEWS {{!}}INDIA TOURISM{{!}}|access-date=2017-03-10|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120419153712/http://www.libdems.org.uk/peers_detail.aspx?name=Lord_Loomba&pPK=d3388ae8-cf3f-435e-9979-92a7aebe7816 Lord Loomba] - website of the Liberal Democrats\n* [http://www.theloombafoundation.org/ The Loomba Foundation]\n* [http://www.theloombafoundation.org/international-widows-day International Widows Day]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120425092319/http://www.rinkugroup.co.uk/index.htm Rinku Group Ltd]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loomba, Raj Loomba, Baron}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa alumni]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:People from Kapurthala]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = The Lord Loomba\n| image = Official portrait of Lord Loomba crop 2.jpg\n|honorific-suffix  = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]\n|office = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start = 12 January 2011<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1943|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Dhilwan]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      =British\n| spouse           = Veena Chaudhry\n| party            = Non-affiliated\n| alma_mater       = [[State University of Iowa]], United States\n}}\n\n'''Rajinder Paul Loomba, Baron Loomba''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 13 November 1943, [[Dhilwan]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India) is a philanthropist, founder and executive chairman of clothing company Loomba Group, and a member of the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/l/23154/Rajinder%20Paul%20%28Raj%29%20Loomba+LOOMBA.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830132829/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/l/23154/Rajinder%20Paul%20(Raj)%20Loomba+LOOMBA.aspx |archivedate=30 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nLoomba was born as one of seven children in Dhilwan, in the state of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India. He was educated at [[Dayanand Anglo-Vedic Schools System|D.A.V. College]], [[Jallandhar]] and at the [[University of Iowa|State University of Iowa]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asian-whoswho.com/viewasian.asp?aid=9 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051030020021/http://www.asian-whoswho.com/viewasian.asp?aid=9 |archivedate=30 October 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> his family moved to England in 1962. Loomba built up his fashion business from scratch, graduating from a stall at [[Widnes]] market to a shop, a wholesale business and then an import company, Rinku Group Ltd. The company has over 200 retail concession outlets in the UK, offices in London, Delhi and China, and supplies major retail groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theloombafoundation.org/sites/default/files/pdf/LR_9501_Loomba.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323050533/http://www.theloombafoundation.org/sites/default/files/pdf/LR_9501_Loomba.pdf |archivedate=23 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLoomba is a member of the [[Rotary Club]] in [[London]], the [[Institute of Directors]] and is a [[Freeman of the City of London]]. He is Chairman of the Friends of the Three Faiths Forum, is Patron of Children In Need India, and is the Founding Patron of the World Punjabi Organisation.<ref>http://globalpf.org/strategic-advisors.html?show=25</ref> He is Vice President of [[Barnardo\u2019s]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/peers_detail.aspx?name=Lord_Loomba&pPK=d3388ae8-cf3f-435e-9979-92a7aebe7816 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419153712/http://www.libdems.org.uk/peers_detail.aspx?name=Lord_Loomba&pPK=d3388ae8-cf3f-435e-9979-92a7aebe7816 |archivedate=19 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and of the Safer London Foundation, a charity backed by the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/rajinder-loomba/90427 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001202505/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/rajinder-loomba/90427 |archivedate=1 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1997 he was named Asian of the Year UK by Asian Who's Who International.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asian-whoswho.com/viewasian.asp?aid=9 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051030020021/http://www.asian-whoswho.com/viewasian.asp?aid=9 |archivedate=30 October 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLoomba is married to Veena Chaudhry, with whom he has two daughters and one son.\n\n==Charity work==\nLoomba has become well known for his fundraising and campaigning concerning the issue of widowhood in the developing world. His mother, Shrimati Pushpa Wati Loomba, was widowed at the age of 37 in India,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theloombafoundation.org/index.php?q=about/inspiration|title=The Loomba Foundation {{!}} Empowering Widows Worldwide {{!}} Children's Education|website=www.theloombafoundation.org|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref> and Loomba experienced first-hand the social and economic discrimination that widows in that country faced.\n\nIt was in his mother\u2019s memory that Loomba set up his charity, [[The Loomba Foundation]], which works to raise awareness of the issue of widowhood and which raises funds to educate the children of poor widows in India and empower widows in other developing countries in south Asia and across Africa. The flagship of the charity\u2019s awareness campaign is [[International Widows Day]], which takes place annually on 23 June, the anniversary of his mother\u2019s widowhood. Following a sustained campaign, on 21 December 2010 the [[United Nations General Assembly]] formally recognised, by unanimous acclaim, 23 June as International Widows Day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/RES/65/189|title=United Nations Official Document|website=www.un.org|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of his contribution to charity, in the [[2008 Birthday Honours]] Loomba was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE);<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58729 |date=14 June 2008 |page=25 |supp=y}}</ref> he received his award from [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] at a ceremony at [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref>http://www.india-server.com/news/nri-entrepreneur-raj-loomba-receives-cbe-5111.html{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==House of Lords==\nOn 12 January 2011 Loomba was ennobled as a [[life peer]] with the name, style and title of '''Baron Loomba''', of [[Moor Park, Hertfordshire|Moor Park]] in the county of [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59672 |date=17 January 2011 |page=80 }}</ref> He took up his seat in the [[House of Lords]] on 13 January 2011, representing the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12178726 | work=BBC News | title=Downton Abbey creator Julian Fellowes takes Lords seat | date=13 January 2011}}</ref> He was introduced to the House on 17 January 2011, supported by the Lords [[Tom McNally, Baron McNally|McNally]] and [[Navnit Dholakia, Baron Dholakia|Dholakia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2011-01-17b.1.0|title=Introduction: Lord Loomba: 17 Jan 2011: House of Lords debates|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref> On 21 January 2011 he gave his maiden speech in the House during a debate on the Rehabilitation of Offenders (Amendment) Bill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libdemvoice.org/lord-raj-loombas-maiden-speech-22840.html|title=Lord Raj Loomba\u2019s maiden speech|website=Liberal Democrat Voice|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref>\n\nLoomba's company, Rinku Group PLC, had previously made a donation of \u00a32,500 to the leadership campaign of [[Nick Clegg]] in December 2007.<ref>https://pefonline.electoralcommission.org.uk/Search/CommonReturnsSearch.aspx?type=basicDonationSearch Electoral Commission website, register of political donations - EC number C0002451 - donation accepted on 17 December 2002</ref> His nomination to the peerage attracted controversy after it emerged that one of the three members of the [[House of Lords Appointments Commission]] who approved his appointment, Liberal Democrat peer Lord Dholakia, had accepted six overseas trips in the previous four years, paid for by Loomba's charitable foundation, the Loomba Trust. Two of the trips, to [[Toronto]] and [[New York City]], took place during the time the Commission was considering Loomba's appointment.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1333712/Lib-Dem-Lord-Dholakia-row-peerage-friend-Raj-Loomba.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | first=Abul | last=Taher | title=Lib Dem in row over peerage for his friend | date=28 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nLoomba donated more than \u00a3350,000 to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] between 2011 and 2013.\n\nIn December 2016, Lord Loomba left the Liberal Democrats and now sits as a [[Non-affiliated members of the House of Lords|non-affiliated]] Peer.  Explaining his decision he said: \"I now wish to concentrate on issues such as human rights, gender equality, education and above all the United Nations\u2019 2030 Sustainable Development Goals\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiagbnews.com/government/lord-raj-loomba-exits-lib-dem-fold/|title=British Indian Lord Raj Loomba 